          Great news, I don't want Shannon! In fact, I want the lack of her. She's shown herself to be selfish, lazy, and foolish. That's giving her the benefit of the doubt, otherwise I'd have to add manipulative. She continues to act more and more like she <span style="font-style: italic;">likes</span> me (I use italics to emphasize the romantic connotation of a normal word), while being less and less accessible. That might have bothered me, but now that I'm sensible I just laugh to myself.<br /><br />It all came together for me yesterday, in a weird moment. She said something about loving Almond Joy, and that brought back a memory of when I was just ending my Duckie phase. What I learned about my Andie (as opposed to Duckie), and how I realized what an idiot I'd been. The good news is that I figured this out about Shannon before being an idiot. Instead, I'm only ashamed of breaking down and getting interested in her. The one thing that kept my interest was a feeling that she was actually going to change for the better after getting rid of her ex. It all looked like it was about to come together when I left, and now there's no trace of it.<br /><br />That's where the laziness comes in, I'm convinced beyond a doubt that her bad qualities are caused by her being too lazy to correct herself. I told myself to give her a chance, that I shouldn't discount her because I was much smarter than her (or rather, that I am more intelligent in general). Thanks to well-meaning friends, I even had an idea in my head about opposites attracting. I see now that she's acid and I'm a reactive metal. Wow, that's more true than I meant it to be. She really is dangerously selfish, she admits to thinking of herself as the only person on the road when driving. How in the hell did I ever ride in a car with her without fearing for my life?! Oh yeah, I was too busy marveling at her eyes. It should've bothered me that I saw them so frequently while she was driving...<br /><br />
